{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Healthcare systems are not yet prepared to manage the complex issues arising from widespread AI use, particularly when the AI itself may be flawed.",
    "Moreover, providers' actions as they interface with AI tools are increasingly monitored and analyzed without fully informed consent, as surveillance processes are embedded in imaging platforms, EHR systems, and QP initiatives-all of which lack adequate safeguards 48.",
    "To address these challenges and protect both clinician and patient data, robust access controls, audit trails 42, transparency standards, and encryption measures are necessary 49.",
    "Transparency in monitoring practices and the establishment of disclosure management systems are crucial, allowing providers to opt-in or out of monitoring where possible 42, 48.",
    "Anonymization and regular security assessments in line with regulations like the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act are also essential 42, 49."
  ],
